description.narrative:
The Girls Advocacy alliance in Ghana strives towards improved implementation of public policies which counteract gender based violence and promote the economic inclusion of girls and young women. The GAA members use the following strategies to ensure that improvements in policy implementation will be sustained in the long-term: 

1.	The organisational capacity support provided to civil society partners aims to strengthen their advocacy efforts in the long run;
2.	The mobilization of a coalition of multiple organisations and actors (change agents) willing and able to hold government agencies accountable, will not only increase the advocacy strength of civil society but also increase the likelihood of effective collective action in the future;
3.	The mobilization of groups of girls and young women and their engagement with formal as well as informal decision-makers will promote a generation of female activists and advocates;
4.	Given the informal (soft) power of traditional chiefs and religious leaders in Ghana, their growing awareness and agency on issues of girls and women’s rights, will have lasting effects on the transformation of gender discriminatory norms and practices
